WORKCOM CONNECT – CRM REQUIREMENTS 
1. INTRODUCTION 
The Workers’ Compensation Fund Control Board (WCFCB) recognizes the 
critical importance of a robust Customer Relationship Management 
(CRM) system. As part of the ERPNext implementation, this document 
outlines the Functional Scope Document (FSD) for the CRM Module, 
detailing the customization requirements necessary to align the CRM 
functionalities with the specific operational needs of the Board. 
WORKCOM CONNECT – CRM REQUIREMENTS 
2. SCOPE 
This document covers the additional functionalities that must be 
incorporated into the ERPNext CRM Module to fully meet WCFCB’s 
needs. It builds upon ERPNext’s base capabilities and ensures a more 
integrated, centralized, and intelligent customer management system.  
Key areas include: 
− Integration with existing contact center systems (Tawk.to, others). 
− Centralized communication via social media and messaging 
platforms. 
− Deployment of customizable surveys and intelligent reporting. 
− Full integration with the CoreBusiness system for unified data 
analytics. 
− Adoption of Artificial Intelligence (AI) for predictive analytics, 
automation, and smart reports. 
WORKCOM CONNECT – CRM REQUIREMENTS 
3. FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS 
3.1 TAWK.TO AND CONTACT CENTER INTEGRATION 
To enhance centralized customer interaction management, the CRM 
Module must seamlessly integrate with Tawk.to and the Board’s existing 
Contact Center system. This integration will ensure that all 
communication touchpoints — calls, chats, emails, and social media 
interactions — are accessible and manageable from a single, unified 
platform, greatly improving efficiency, response times, and customer 
satisfaction. 
The integration must be bi-directional, allowing real-time data exchange 
between ERPNext CRM and the Contact Center, ensuring consistency 
across systems. 
Requirements include: 
− Integration with all major social media platforms for centralized 
communications. 
− Third-party bulk messaging integration allowing selection of 
messaging channels. 
− Full call center integration for real-time call management. 
3.1.1 INTEGRATION WITH ALL SOCIAL MEDIA PLATFORMS 
To ensure centralized management of customer communications, the 
CRM must fully aggregate and unify messages from all major social 
media platforms, including WhatsApp, Facebook Messenger, Instagram, 
Twitter (X), Telegram, and LinkedIn. 
The goal is to allow customer service agents and other Board users to 
handle all client interactions through a single interface, without the need 
to log into multiple external platforms. 
Centralized Communication Hub 
Messages from all integrated platforms must appear in a single inbox 
view, linked to the customer’s CRM profile for full interaction history and 
context. 
One-Click Multi-Platform Broadcasting 
When creating an announcement, blog post, or update, users should be 
able to select multiple platforms and broadcast the content with a single 
WORKCOM CONNECT – CRM REQUIREMENTS 
click. This ensures consistent messaging across all customer channels 
while saving significant time and effort. 
Generative AI Integration for Content Composure 
CRM should integrate with AI writing services (e.g., OpenAI, Google 
Gemini, or similar models) to assist users in composing professional, 
clear, and structured messages. 
This would allow: 
− Grammar and tone checks. 
− Auto-suggested posts based on the announcement topic. 
− Rewriting or summarization tools to tailor messages per platform 
(e.g., a shorter version for X, a formal one for LinkedIn etc.) 
AI-Based Auto-Responses 
Incoming queries on social media should be answered automatically 
using intelligent AI Bots trained specifically on the Board's processes, 
services, FAQs, and common inquiries. 
The system should: 
− Recognize common customer questions and answer them 
instantly. 
− Escalate complex queries to human agents when necessary. 
− Continuously learn from previous interactions to improve future 
responses. 
3.1.2 CRM BOARD'S VIRTUAL ASSISTANT – FAQ HANDLING 
To enhance customer self-service and reduce manual workload, a CRM 
Board Virtual Assistant (Bot) must be deployed across all integrated 
platforms. 
Features of the CRM Board Bot: 
Automated FAQs Management 
The Bot must be trained with a detailed FAQ database covering key 
topics such as beneficiary services, employer assessments, claims 
procedures, contribution processes, and Board contacts. 
Multilingual Support 
Where necessary, the Bot should support Zambia’s key languages 
besides English, like Bemba, Nyanja, and Tonga, ensuring inclusivity. 
WORKCOM CONNECT – CRM REQUIREMENTS 
Escalation Protocols 
For inquiries beyond the Bot’s capability (e.g., complex case-specific 
questions), the Bot must automatically escalate the ticket to a live agent 
while transferring conversation context. 
Personalized Interactions 
When identifying returning customers, the Bot should greet them by 
name, reference previous tickets, and personalize the conversation for a 
better customer experience. 
AI Learning and Updates 
The FAQ database must be updated regularly, and the Bot should use 
machine learning to recognize and adapt to new types of questions 
emerging over time. 
